#: src/0599-default-object-bound.md:88
msgid ""
"This RFC proposes to use the context in which an object type appears to "
"derive a sensible default. Specifically, the default begins as `'static`.  "
"Type constructors like `&` or user-defined structs can alter that default "
"for their type arguments, as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0599-default-object-bound.md:93
msgid "The default begins as `'static`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0599-default-object-bound.md:94
msgid ""
"`&'a X` and `&'a mut X` change the default for object bounds within `X` to "
"be `'a`"
msgstr ""

#: src/0599-default-object-bound.md:95
msgid ""
"The defaults for user-defined types like `SomeType<X>` are driven by the "
"where-clauses defined on `SomeType`, see the next section for details. The "
"high-level idea is that if the where-clauses on `SomeType` indicate the `X` "
"will be borrowed for a lifetime `'a`, then the default for objects appearing "
"in `X` becomes `'a`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0599-default-object-bound.md:101
msgid ""
